04482nmm a2200613Ia 9780520391819DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203918197 a10.1525/97805203918192doi  a(DE-B1597)642436  a(OCoLC)1356002971  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN2287.D322 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a792.702/8092 B1 aJacobson, Matthew Frye, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDancing Down the Barricades :bSammy Davis Jr. and the Long Civil Rights Era /cMatthew Frye Jacobson. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAuthor’s Note -- tPreface: The Long Civil Rights Era -- t1. Star Rising at Twilight -- t2. “A Concentrated Bunch of Haters” -- t3. The All-Negro Cast, and Other Black Spaces -- t4. The Vegas Strip, Network TV, and Other White Spaces -- t5. “Division Is Not Our Destiny” -- t6. Writing Wrongs in Yes I Can -- t7. “The Skin Commits You” -- tCoda -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA deep dive into racial politics, Hollywood, and Black cultural struggles for liberation as reflected in the extraordinary life and times of Sammy Davis Jr. Through the lens of Sammy Davis Jr.'s six-decade career in show business—from vaudeville to Vegas to Broadway, Hollywood, and network TV—Dancing Down the Barricades examines the workings of race in American culture. The title phrase holds two contradictory meanings regarding Davis's cultural politics: Did he dance the barricades down, as he liked to think, or did he simply dance down them, as his more radical critics would have it? Davis was at once a pioneering, barrier-busting, anti–Jim Crow activist and someone who was widely associated with accommodationism and wannabe whiteness. Historian Matthew Frye Jacobson attends to both threads, analyzing how industry norms, productions, scripts, roles, and audience expectations and responses were all framed by race against the backdrop of a changing America. In the spirit of better understanding Davis's life and career, Dancing Down the Barricades examines the complexities of his constraints, freedoms, and choices for what they reveal about Black history and American political culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aEntertainerszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520391819?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520391819423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520391819/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131913-1  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2023  aZDB-23-DGGb2023